How would you solve this equation by factoring?<n><n><n>```python<n>        <n>       2y  + 3x= 9<n><n>```<n>Output:<n>-In this question given an equation y = (2√ó3)-1/2. which means the two terms that are negative.<n>-To make the equation positive multiply the equation by two and add one.<n>-The above equation will become 4y-2x= 10<n>-At this step find the greatest common factor of both 4 +10. it is given as 4 and 10.<n>So it means that 4x-5x is the greatest common factor of the both 4 and 1 is left with the equation. Choices:  A: chicago B: street C: little italy D: food court E: capital cities<n>Output:		"answer is c, Little Italy"<n>So the given input is given above...so we need to define which options are given in correct order then only we will be able to find the out put.<n>So the input is correct order.<n><n>#### <n>### Solution:<n>```java<n><n>import java.util.*;<n><n>public class Solution {<n><n> public static void main(String[] args) {<n><n>  Scanner s=new Scanner(System.in);<n><n>  String line=s.nextLine();   <n>  	int i= 0 ;<n>  	int j= 0 ;<n><n>  	boolean first=true;            <n><n>  	    for(int q= 0 ; q <= i; q++)              <n>  	    { <n>  	        if(line.charAt(q)  == 'p')   <n>  	        {<n>  	           System.out.println("\nCorrect answer is: "+ "b"); <n>  	           return ;<n><n>//we are finding out the last character of the string<n><n>	        }<n><n><n>  	    }<n><n><n>   System.out.print(line.charAt((j))) ; <n>  	{  <n>  	     for (int q = 0; q <= j ;q++)<n>  	       	    {<n>  	          if(line.charCaseAt(q)== 'q')<n>  <n>  	       	       if(i == j  )   System.out.println("answer is : "+ "e");  <n>  <n>       <n>   	  	          else if(Line.charAt(j)== 'l')<n>  <n>   System.out.println ("answer the correct order is : "+ "e"  );<n>   else if( first == true )<n>   <n>   System.out().println("answer the correct order is C D E");<n>  		if (i == j)<n>  <n>   		System.out.println("Correct answer is: "+"c" );      <n>          		return ;       // return in the above statement to break the loop<n>  		                      <n>		          }       <n><n>                i=i+1 <n>                j=j+1 ;     //increasing the index<n>        		  }  //end of for loop

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: the mean of 30 values was 140. it was detected on rechecking that one value 145 was wrongly copied as 135 for the computation of the mean. find the correct mean. a ) 151, b ) 140.33, c ) 152, d ) 148, e ) none of the above<n>Output: "corrected mean = 140 √ó 30 ‚àí 135 + 145 / 30 = 4200 ‚àí 135 + 145 / 30 = 4210 / 30 = 140.33 answer b"<n>So the final answer is b<n><n>Input:You can share files with someone if you have a connection to a what? Choices:  A: freeway B: radio C: wires D: computer network E: electrical circuit<n>Output:		Connection to a what? A: Freeway B: Radio C: Wires D: Computer Network E: Electric circuit, answer C<n><n>-----------------<n>```python<n><n>## Import libraries<n>from collections import Counter<n>from operator import itemgetter<n><n>## Write code here<n>def file_sharing(data):<n>    mean = data[1]+data[2]<n>    mean = float(mean)<n>    # print(mean)<n>    if data[3]=='A':<n>        difference = mean - 50<n>    else:<n>        difference = mean + 50<n>    if data[4]=='A': <n>        difference = mean * 2<n>    total_file = data[-1]<n>    print(f'Corrected value = {mean * 30 - total_file + difference / 30}= 5000 - {total_file}+ {difference / 30}')<n>    print(f"Corrected mean = {mean * 10 - 10*10 + 10*20} / {40}")<n>file_input = input()<n><n>result=(file_input.split(" "))<n>## Create dictionary(dict is abbreviation for dictionary)<n>dct = {}<n>for i in range(len(result)):<n>    dct[result[i+1]] = result[:i+1]<n><n>## Get count from Counter object<n>file = ''<n>for j in range(len(dct)):<n>    if dct[j]=='A': file-=1<n>    elif dct[j] == 'B': file+=1<n>    else:<n>pass<n>print(file*file,file)<n>if file==0: answer='A'<n>if file==1: answer='B'<n>if file>1: answer='C'<n>if file>3: answer='E'<n><n>## Remove blank space from Counter object<n>print(counter)<n>counter = [float(c.strip()) for c in counter.split(',')]<n>counter.remove(' '+counter[-1]+'-')<n><n># Compute average and variance.<n># print(counter)<n>mean = sum(counter/len(counter))<n>variance = sum((val**2 for val in counter)<n>                    /len(counter))

Since perseverance is uncountable the sentence " not perseverance but...." is valid and the answer is d <n>Input: I am on the ____ train,  Choices:  A : train B : trains C) to train,, D. of train, e) none of the above <n>Output: the correct answer is A train. " am " is a verb which refers to who is being referred to. In order to refer to the same person, " I " has to be used. " I " refers to a noun because it takes the article. Noun should be followed by determiner before counting noun then finally the countable noun, and then a verb " am" . Hence the answer <n>Input : I am on the ___ train.  Choices:  a train B : trains C ) to train, d) of train <n>Output : Answer d " of train". " I " is a pronoun which refers to the person being referred too.  The person being referred is "I " so it is a nominative pronoun. Since it is the subject of the sentence, it has to be in the nominative case. Nominative case is to be preceded by determiner and then followed by countable noun.   " I" is preceded by " a " then followed by " am/ are " and then a train . "of" is in the nominative case because " I" is the

Choices:  A: income tax B: satisfaction C: sorrow D: ocean E: bill collectors to happy<n>Output:		"bill collectors"<n><n>```<n>function main() {<n>    let nums = [141, 118, 174, 140].sort();<n>    console.log(getMean(nums, 30, 1));<n>}<n><n>function getMean(nums = [145], n = 1, ans = false) {<n>    const len = nums.length;<n>    if (ans == true) return 0;<n>    if (len > n) return 0;//correct mean<n>    if (ans === undefined) ans = false;<n>    return nums.reduce((a, b) => ((a % 2 === 0)? a + b : a * 10 + b)) / len;<n>}<n>```<n><n>## Problem 3:<n><n>```<n>function Solution() {<n>    const solution = [1, 3, 3, 97, 8, 238, 87, 223, 5].sort()<n>    console.log(`I love to ${ solution[0] }`);<n>}<n>```<n>

Choices:  A: jerusalem B: jewish community C: middle east D: city E: mosque<n>Output:		<n>So answer is b<n><n><n><n><n><n>#!/usr/bin/python3<n><n>import pynput<n>import random<n><n>class left():<n><n>    def __init__(self):<n><n>        self.left = pynput.mouse.Button.left<n>        self.right = pynput. mouse.Button.right<n>    def buttonClick(self, mouse_position, pressed, release, button):<n><n>        if mouse_position == self.right:<n>         pressed = pressed<n>         release = release<n>         button = self.right<n><n>    def handleEvents(self, event):<n>        if event.type == self.left:<n>            self.buttonClick(event, pressed=False, release=True, button=self.left)<n>            print("left pressed")<n><n>        if event.pressed == False:<n>            print("realease")<n><n><n>if __name__ == '__main__':<n><n>    while True:<n><n>        pressed, released, button = left.buttonClick(pynput.mouse.Position(x=50, y=40), pressed=True, release=False, button = left.left)<n>        print(pressed, released, button)<n>\end{code}<n><n>Comment: It's best practice *not* to use `import *`. It violates [PEP-8](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/)'s usage of `import`. Consider reading the full docs on [importing modules](https://docs.python.org/2/tutorial/modules.html#the-module-search-path) to avoid such problems.

What is meant by a random sample of a data set<n># What is meant b y a population<n><n>A random sample is what <n>you would have if you <n>really were <n>sampl3ing.<n> <n># How many possible values are there for each variable. Choice is to be made from the correct data set.<n><n># Can be expressed in terms of frequency distribution<n><n># What do you mean by population. When is it important to know the population of a data set<n><n>We do not know the exact population or values which make up the data set. <n><n>### Instruction:Answer the question below.<n><n>What is meant by population? Explain when it is possible <n>to draw conclusions about a population on the basis of a sample of the population.<n><n>Answer: The population is the entire sample of items. A random sample is one that includes a fixed percentage. Random samples represent the population well in the sense that the items are picked with a certain degree of randomization. Therefore, statistical sampling is useful if the population of interest is very large.<n>If it is small or very small, then this data sampling method will not work. We are only trying to use a sample to represent the population.<n><n>Output: An algorithm for data sampling is to first take a random selection from the entire population. This process is called sampling without replacement. After sampling the desired number of items, this sample will be used instead of the entire population. This is called a systematic sample. This systematic sample can become biased. Instead the probability can be weighted so the systematic sample gets the correct results.<n><n># Find the mean and variance for the following:<n><n>Input: The data set 0 0 4 0 3 0 5 3 3 0 1 2 0 0 5 0 0 6 is the height of <n>five boys in a class. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: the mean of 30 values was 140. it was detected on rechecking that one value 145 was wrongly copied as 135 for the computation of the mean. find the correct mean. a ) 151, b ) 140.33, c ) 152, d ) 148, e ) none of the above<n>Output: "corrected mean = 140 √ó 30 ‚àí 135 + 145 / 30 = 4200 ‚àí 135 + 145 / 30 = 4210 / 30 = 140.33 answer b"<n>So the final answer is b<n><n>Input:A blowfish lives free. Choices:  A: fish market B: pet shop C: great outdoors D: river E: little mermaid<n>Output:		Blowfish: He lives in a pet shop<n><n>### Instruction: Find if the input is palindrome and if it is not, then reverse it.<n><n>### Instructions:<n>Let us divide the input word into three subgroups.<n>1. First word<n>2. Second word<n>3. Remaining letters<n><n>Let us now take the first word.<n>We need to find the count of 'e' in the first word. The sum of the count of the first, second and the remaining letters will be equal to the whole word length.<n><n>### Steps to solve:<n>Let A = number of times 'e' occurs in the input string<n>Let B = Total count of letters in the input string (excluding 'e')<n>Now let us find A and B <n>```<n>if "a" == inputstring[1], then b = b + 1<n>if "a"!= inputstring[1], B = B + 1<n>if 'a' == inputstring[1]  <n>    A = A + 1<n>else<n>    B = b + A<n>```<n>This algorithm is running time is O(n) because it will take time O(n) to calculate B.It will take O(1) to increment B because it is a constant <n><n>This algorithm is space complexity is O(1) because it is constant that is we don't have to take any extra space to store the string input value.<n><n>### Out-put :<n><n>Let E be some character in the string, say 'x'. We know that the first word will contain at least E 1 or more times. Now<n>Let A = Number of times E occurs in the first word and Let B = the sum of the word count(excluding E)<n><n>Now, sum of the A is equal to sum of the B + E<n><n>For the Second word, E occurs only once and the sum of the word length is B - 1<n>Since the Remaining letters are of length n - B, hence the sum of the letters will be n - B.<n><n>Now we know that, <n>The sum of word count is BL, where B and L denotes the total numbers of letters in length L.<n>the sum of the count of letters in each word including the second word and remaining letters is equal to n - B if the second word is not the first

Choices: A: 365 and 387 B: 383 and 379 C: 744 and 11189 D: 662 and 9973 E: 279 and 391<n>Output: "My answer choice was A; your answer choice was B. Both are right."<n><n>## Sample Code (python)<n>def bai(n,arr,pos):<n>    if(pos > n):<n>        return 0<n>    else:<n>        sum=0<n>        for i in range(0,pos):<n>            sum+=n<n>        if(arr[pos]==0):<n>            sum-=1<n>        arr[pos]-=sum<n>        return bai(n, arr, pos+1)<n><n>if __name__=="__main__":<n>    n=int(input())<n>    arr=[i for i in range(2,n+1)]<n>    pos=0<n>    try:<n>        arr[len(arr)]<n>    except:<n>        pass<n><n>    arr.sort()<n>    ans=-1<n>    sum=0<n>    for i in range(len(arr)):<n>        sum+=arr[i]<n>        if(sum>=n):<n>            ans=pos<n>    if(ans==-1):<n>        ans=0<n>        for j in range(len(array)):<n>            if(arr[j]+1==sum):<n>                if(arr[j]==1):<n>                    ans=1<n>                break<n>    print(ans)<n>

Find the 99% confidence interval for the true population mean.<n>Output Answer: There is 1% or 2% chance that the true mean is less than 67 or more than 67 since 67 is a population average or mean.<n>So here the 99% Confidence interval for the mean of population is 67 + 2 or ‚àí67 ‚àí 2<n><n>Now we would apply the formula<n><n>99% C.I = Œº ¬± %. Z ( 2/2 ) % 2 where Z is the normal score z-score<n><n>% in this formula is a % as % = 1% or 1 -.01, so % is.01<n>The z score is ‚àö(67^2 - 67^2)<n><n>67 ^ 2 = 4701, z ^ 2 = ‚àö4701<n><n>z = sqrt(.586)<n>Z = ¬±.586 ‚àö(2) (0.01) 2<n>Answer: 67 + (‚àí.446) = 66.55 or<n>67 ‚Äì (.446) =.6752 (more than 4th place)<n>or<n>67 + (0.446) œÉ = 67.24 4th = 66.86 or<n>67 ‚àí (.446) Œº = 67.659 1st = 67.75<n><n>Input: The mean of an unrepresentative sample Œæ drawn from a given population Œº is found to be 92.4<n>The true mean ¬µ can be estimated as --------------<n>Output answer: a) Œ¥, b) œï, c) ¬µ, d) 55.12, e) 92.5 %<n><n>The final answer is b<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: the mean of 30 values was 140. it was detected on rechecking that one value 145 was wrongly copied as 135 for the computation of the mean. find the correct mean. a ) 151, b ) 140.33, c ) 152, d ) 148, e ) none of the above<n>Output: "corrected mean = 140 √ó 30 ‚àí 135 + 145 / 30 = 4200 ‚àí 135 + 145 / 30 = 4210 / 30 = 140.33 answer b"<n>So the final answer is b<n><n>Input:Where are you likely to find a professional prostitute? Choices:  A: new york B: whorehouse C: street corner D: corner of two streets E: brother<n>Output:		new york<n><n>Input: A. Which of the following is the simplest fraction? Choices A. 5/6 B. 8/9 C. 13/15 D. None of the above<n>Output:"13/15 ans"<n><n>Input:If a soccer team scores 2 goals. It would be declared.a) Winner,b) tie c) looser,d) none<n>Output:"win"<n><n>Input:Find the greatest number between 30 and 40?<n><n>Input:a.How much 2.2 and 1.8.<n><n><img width="367" alt="img1" src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/90587022/166030102-1ef2a888-33be-44b8-952a-510a2da16268.jpg"><n><n>### Solution:<n><n>First step:<n><n>Find the mean of 31 values.<n><n>$$ \bar{x} = 31 \cdot \frac{135 + 200 + 160 + 50 + 45 + 15  + 131 + 135 + \cdots + 140}{31 * 2} $$<n><n>Therefore.<n><n>$$ \begin{split}\bar{x} &=\dfrac{135 +200 +160 +50 +45 +15 +\cdots+140}{343} \\ &= \dfrac{135+343+160+50+45+15+\cdots+140+609}{330+330+280+280}\\&= \dfrac{609}{755} ~~~~~~~~~~(\textrm{since 135=75})\\ &= 0.805\end{split}$$<n><n>Thus.<n><n>$$ \textrm{The incorrect mean is} ~134$$<n><n>Second step:<n><n>For calculating the corrected mean:<n><n>$$\textrm{Corrected Mean = Original Mean ‚àí ((31/31)*(Incorrect Mean))}$$<n>$$

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: the mean of 30 values was 140. it was detected on rechecking that one value 145 was wrongly copied as 135 for the computation of the mean. find the correct mean. a ) 151, b ) 140.33, c ) 152, d ) 148, e ) none of the above<n>Output: "corrected mean = 140 √ó 30 ‚àí 135 + 145 / 30 = 4200 ‚àí 135 + 145 / 30 = 4210 / 30 = 140.33 answer b"<n>So the final answer is b<n><n>Input:If you're betting with a shark, where are you likely playing? Choices:  A: aquarium B: mediterranean sea C: south pacific D: pool hall E: pacific ocean<n>Output:		The final answer is C, Meditarranian sea<n><n>#!/bin/bash<n><n>read -p "Enter the mean of 18 values :" A ;<n>read -p "The mean has been computed to be : " B<n><n>if [ $A -eq $B ]; then<n>        echo "The mean of 18 numbers is : " $B<n>    else<n>        read -p "One value 145 entered as 145 for computation of the mean. Correct the value & recalculate the mean. Enter the sum of the mean & correct value. " ans && sed -i "/145/c ${ans}" data.txt<n>        read -p "$0" data.txt<n>        let "i = 1"<n>        awk '{sum+=$4}END{print sum/i+1}' < data.txt # data.txt has one value per line<n>        read -p "${ans} + corrected number" ans2 && sed -i "/${ans2}/c ${answer}" data.txt<n><n>        if [ `grep -c ${ans2} data.txt` -eq 1 ];then<n>                echo "corrected mean = ${ans},${ans2}"<n>        else<n>                echo "correct answer = ${ans},${answer}"<n>        fi<n>fi<n><n>```<n><n>* * *<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>In the first case this script is checking if the mean is equal to what was entered, if yes it prints it otherwise, it enters the mean and reads the number of corrections to make, then the script makes the required corrections and searches for its value in the data.txt<n><n>In the second case instead of checking if the mean is written correctly, the program asks if you have played with a shark, if so it uses the command "awk" to look for all the values with the character A, once it finds them it deletes them and then it prints the remaining values in descending order, then the program does the opposite to look for answers<n><n>* * * <n><n># How it works<n>In this script we used the command grep from the shell to search for a string contained in the data.txt, it has the following expression:<n><n>`(./script.sh)grep "character1" data_location`<n><n>The grep command searches for the string character1, and the data_location

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: the mean of 30 values was 140. it was detected on rechecking that one value 145 was wrongly copied as 135 for the computation of the mean. find the correct mean. a ) 151, b ) 140.33, c ) 152, d ) 148, e ) none of the above<n>Output: "corrected mean = 140 √ó 30 ‚àí 135 + 145 / 30 = 4200 ‚àí 135 + 145 / 30 = 4210 / 30 = 140.33 answer b"<n>So the final answer is b<n><n>Input:The man needed balls of cotton, where should he look? Choices:  A: south B: georgia C: north carolina D: pocket E: medicine cabinet<n>Output:		 a = not the right answer<n><n>Input:The 1/8th of a mile is also equal to approximately how many yards? Choices: A) 15 B) 17 1/8 C) 17 B) 1/8 D) 15.4 1/8<n>Output:b<n><n>#!/bin/python<n>import sys<n><n>d=0 #initialize d to zero<n>n = int(raw_input())<n><n>c = float(raw_input()) #c = cofactor value to multiply with <n>g=int(raw_input()) <n>r = n / (n +2)<n>if abs(g)< n: # g is smaller than n so g should not be a float, but an int<n>    print "corrected mean = ", r*g<n>else:<n>    w = round(1000000*g/r) #g is bigger than n so g should be treated as large float<n>    d = round(10 *(d+floor(d*w*n/(n+g)))/ (n+g)) #d = value for the correction<n>    s = round(d*floor(d= n/(n+g))) # s = new value for final answer<n>    r = r/s #new r = old r/ new s<n>    print "correct answer = r", r<n>

What percentage of the trousers are damaged?<n>Output: 6.2%<n><n># Instruction:Answer the instructions below. Note that your answer will be sent to a Tutor (Marking Tutor). Please ensure your answers are neatly formed.<n><n>Exploring Numbers and operations<n><n>Find the sum of the first 7 odd numbers below:<n><n><n>Odd Number:<n>6<n>8<n>10<n>12<n>14<n>16<n>18<n>9<n>7<n><n>## Solution by Python<n><n>In mathematics, the odd numbers are the members of the set of integers beginning with 1 and continuing to infinity that precede the even numbers, which are by definition numbers that can be divided by two evenly. For example, the odd numbers 1, 3, 5, 7,... are the successors to the 0. Likewise, the even numbers are the successors to 2. A set of consecutive natural numbers is called an arithmetic progression (AP), and if the difference between each successive pair is the same, then we say the progression is by "d", where d is a fixed number, known as the common difference or difference. If the progression is by 1, it is called a geometric progression

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: the mean of 30 values was 140. it was detected on rechecking that one value 145 was wrongly copied as 135 for the computation of the mean. find the correct mean. a ) 151, b ) 140.33, c ) 152, d ) 148, e ) none of the above<n>Output: "corrected mean = 140 √ó 30 ‚àí 135 + 145 / 30 = 4200 ‚àí 135 + 145 / 30 = 4210 / 30 = 140.33 answer b"<n>So the final answer is b<n><n>Input:He had been doing favors for everybody at work, it was frustrating not getting any what for it? Choices:  A: let down B: respect C: illness D: satisfaction E: gratitude<n>Output:		"C: Illness"<n><n><n><n>#!/usr/bin/python3<n><n>from typing import List, Tuple<n><n><n>def is_pal:<n>    def f(ch: List[Tuple[int, int],...]) -> bool:<n>        ch2 = ch<n>        while len(ch2) > 1:<n>            if ch2[-1][0] > ch2[-2][0]:<n>                ch2.pop()<n>        if ch2[-1] == (0, 1):<n>            return True<n>        if ch2 >= (0, 2):<n>            return False<n>        else:<n>            return True<n><n>    return f<n><n><n>def isop:<n>    def f1(ch: List[int]) -> bool:<n><n>        def f2(ch: List[List[Tuple[int]],...]) -> List[int,...]:<n>            ch2 = ch<n>            if isinstance(ch, list):<n>                tmp = 0<n>                while len(ch2[0]) >= 2:<n>                    if ch2[len(ch2)-2] == (0, ch2[len(<n>                        ch2)-1]):<n>                        ch2[len(tmp) - 2] = (0, tmp)<n>                if len(tmp) >= 3:<n>                    tmp.pop()<n>                ch2 += list(tmp)<n>            return ch<n><n>        tmp = 0<n>        for ch2 in ch:<n>            if (ch2 == (1, (0, tmp))):<n>                return False<n>            if (ch == (0, tmp)):<n>                return False<n>        return True<n><n>    def f2(ch):<n>        if isinstance(ch[0][0], str):<n><n>            def f3(tmp):<n>                if id(tmp) == id(ch3):<n>                    return True<n>            if (is_pal(tmp) = f) and (isop(list(ch3)))):<n>                return True<n>            f3(tmp)<n>        return False<n>    ch3 = ''<n>    while len(ch3[0]) < 3:<n>        tmp = 1<n>        if isinstance((ch, list)) and ch:<n>            ch3 += '\n'.join(ch)<n>            temp

That is, there exists exactly one correct answer.<n><n>For example, it is impossible to be a teacher and a student at the same time. Therefore, the options in a single choice question is only one correct answer (one-choice question).<n><n>Another example: it is impossible to have more than two chairs in one room. Therefore when there is asked the question: "Is John sitting?" It is impossible for John to sit on more than 2 chairs.<n><n>### Solution - Single Choice<n><n>The following is a multiple choice questions (MCQ) and it have 5 options:<n><n>	question1 (MCQ): "What do you think is the correct answer?"<n>	MCQ:<n>		a) Option 1<n>		b) Option 2<n>		c) Option 3<n>		d) Option 4<n>		e) Option 5<n><n><n>### Test Case for Input -> "corrected mean =140 √ó 60 ‚àí 130 + 145/60 = 42,000 ‚àí 85 + 85/60 ="

Choices:  A: pocket B: office supply store C: friend's house D: desk drawer E: city hall<n>Output:		"City hall, to register a complaint"<n>So the final ans is E<n>#!/usr/bin/python<n><n>#!/usr/binom/python<n><n>import sys<n>from optparse import OptionParser<n><n>parser = OptionParser( "puzzler.py" )<n><n><n>options, arguments = parser.parse_args()<n><n># get first line:<n># argv[1] -> filename<n>args = arguments.split()<n>if len(args)==1:<n>    args[0] = sys.argv[1]<n><n># get filename:<n>if __name__ == "__main__":<n>    if not args[0].endswith( ".puzzle" ):<n>        args.append( '--puzzleFile:', args[0] + ".puzzle" )<n>    del args[0]<n><n><n># the argv will be the puzzle filename with optional command line arguments <n>args["argument"]  = "A: pocket  B: office supply store  C: friend's  house  D: desk dra\n\<n>    \nE: city hall" <n><n><n>if len(args[0].split(" ")) == 1:<n>    args["puzzler_result"] = "A"<n>elif len(args[0])<4 or args[0][-1]!= "'":<n>    args["puzzer_result"] = "B"<n>else:<n>    args["answer"] = "E"<n>except Exception,e:<n>    print e<n>    sys.exit(1)<n><n>sys.stdout.flush()<n>fps = open( args["puzzler"], "r" )<n><n># parse each line of fps to the correct method<n>for line in fps:<n>    args["line"] = line<n>    args["line_split"] = line.split()<n>    args["linearg"] = args["line"].split( " " ) [0]<n>    args["lineout"]  = args["line"].lower().split( args["line_split_string"] ) [1]<n>    args["new_line"] = ""<n><n><n># print all the data to the new file<n>fps2 = open( args[0], "w" )<n>for line in args:<n>  fps2.write

An expression can never be both TRUE and FALSE.<n><n>The results TRUE and FALSE have truth values of 1 and 0 respectively in C#.<n>```csharp<n>bool expression = expression1 && expression2;<n>```<n><n>### Question29:<n>What happens, if one of the two values is FALSE?<n>When both expressions are evaluated in the if statement, even if only one of the two is TRUE, the result is still TRUE. However, if the values are equal, then one result is returned instead of both.<n><n>You can write conditional operators in two ways. Which method would you pick in this case:<n>```csharp<n>if (condition1) {<n>    return result1;<n><n>if (condition2) {<n>    return condition2;<n>}<n><n>return condition1;<n>```<n>In all 3 scenarios, only one result will be returned.<n><n>### Question4:<n>What is the difference between a ternary conditional and an if else in c#?<n>Use a ternary operator when you want to make the conditional evaluation as concise as possible.<n>In a ternary operator, just like in an if statement, you have an expression of the result, followed by an assignment operator, followed by a true or false value

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: the mean of 30 values was 140. it was detected on rechecking that one value 145 was wrongly copied as 135 for the computation of the mean. find the correct mean. a ) 151, b ) 140.33, c ) 152, d ) 148, e ) none of the above<n>Output: "corrected mean = 140 √ó 30 ‚àí 135 + 145 / 30 = 4200 ‚àí 135 + 145 / 30 = 4210 / 30 = 140.33 answer b"<n>So the final answer is b<n><n>Input:It had a beach with shallow water, while not the ocean this was a hot spot all the locals enjoyed on the what? Choices:  A: swimming pool B: pond C: lake D: bathe in E: childrens pool<n>Output:		Ans:B<n><n>#!/bin/bash<n><n>a)<n>sum=`echo $1 | awk '{total += $1;++count}END{printf("%s %s\n", total, count)}'`<n>b)<n>rm -f results<n>for f in *.txt; do<n>	sum=$(cat "$f")<n>	sum=$(echo "$$sum" | tr,'')<n>	let count=count+1<n>	sum=`echo $sum | awk '{total += ($sum-1)/2}END{printf("%0.f %d\n", total,count)}'`<n>	echo -e "$sum \t$count\n" >> results<n>done<n>	diff -u results<n><n><n>sum=0<n>count=0<n>echo "What is the sum of 14 + 19  & 19 + 4?"<n>read inp<n>if [[ $inp = 19 && $inp = 4 ]]; then<n>	sum=$(echo $inp | awk '{print 4-0*($1+1)}')<n>	count=$(echo $inp)<n>fi<n>echo "Answer $sum $count"<n>
